[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] '''Sir Hugh Henry Darby Tothill''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KCB|KCMG|KCVO}} (14 March 1865 â€“ 25 September 1927) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer who served as [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Captain]] in [[World War I]] and went on to become [[Commander-in-chief]] of [[East Indies Station]] following his promotion to Admiral.

==History==
Tothill was promoted to [[Lieutenant]] in 1888,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=25772|supp=|startpage=15|date=3 January 1888|accessdate=25 September 2010}}</ref> [[Commander (Royal Navy)|Commander]] in January 1901,<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=27263 |date=4 January 1901 |startpage=82 }}</ref> and subsequently to [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Captain]] in 1906.<ref>[http://www.admirals.org.uk/admirals/individual.php?RecNo=392 Royal Navy Flag Officers 1904-1945]</ref> Having received command of the [[HMS Illustrious (1896)|HMS ''Illustrious'']] by 1908<ref>[http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/navy_list_1908_ship_h_to_l.htm Navy List 1908]</ref> and the [[HMS Lancaster (1902)|HMS ''Lancaster'']] by 1911,<ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~cbye/ftweb/00census1911/census1911a_012.htm 1911 Census Results]</ref> he served in [[World War I]], commanding the [[HMS Conqueror (1911)|HMS ''Conqueror'']] at the [[Battle of Jutland]] in 1916.<ref>[http://www.gwpda.org/naval/jut03lst.htm Battle of Jutland - Royal Navy Ships and Commanding Officers]</ref>

After the war he was appointed [[Fourth Sea Lord]] in 1917<ref>[http://www.fotw.net/flags/gb-raf2.html Royal Air Force flag: timeline for introduction]</ref> and served as [[Commander-in-chief]] at [[East Indies Station]] from 1919 to 1921<ref>[http://janus.lib.cam.ac.uk/db/node.xsp?id=EAD%2FGBR%2F0115%2FY3011C-N%2FY3011K Sir Henry Hesketh Bell Collection] Janus</ref> before becoming Admiral Commanding the Reserves in 1923.<ref>Naval and Military, The Times, 24 July 1923</ref> He retired from military service in 1926<ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19261231.2.33&l=mi&e=-------10--1----0-- Service Notes] Evening Post, 1926</ref> and died in 1927.<ref>Obituary: Admiral Sir Hugh Tothill, The Times, 27 September 1927</ref>

